# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
`genCall` is a function which calls the next yielding element and if it is not done yielding it keeps calling itself in turns to the point of resolution.
Same functionality is needed when we throw something to generator which is handled by explicitThrow param which is by default false.
while cancelling we simply call `genCall( "Cancelled",true);` that handles the rest for us.

Note within `genCall` there are two try catch blocks, first one simply rejects as, if there is some error that is now handled and happens during generator function execution it should be rejected. While in the second one we are seeking if there is some error thrown from the promise that is returned in that case we simply chain that value to next call. 
# Code
```
function cancellable<T>(generator: Generator<Promise<any>, T, unknown>): [() => void, Promise<T>] {
    let res,rej,done=false;  
    let promise: Promise<T> = new Promise(async (rs,rj)=>{
        rej=rj;
        res=rs
    })
    async function genCall(val?:any,explicitThrow:boolean=false){
     let genData;
     try{
     genData = explicitThrow?generator.throw(val): generator.next(val);
    }catch(err){
        rej(err);
        return;
    }
     try{
        if(genData.done){
            let result= await genData.value
            done=true;
            res(result);
            return;
        }
        else{
              let result= await genData.value
              genCall(result);
        }
     }
     catch(err){
                  genCall( err,true);
     }

    }
    genCall();
    return [()=>{    
                try {
                    genCall( "Cancelled",true);
                } 
                catch (e) {
                    rej(e);
                }
    },promise]
};

