Can someone explain how reset is returning currentCount in reset()

 `var createCounter = function(init) {
  let currentCount = init;
  return {
    increment: () => ++currentCount,
    decrement: () => --currentCount,
    reset: () => (currentCount = init),
  }
};`

can anybody explain whats wong with my code?

var counter = {
        "increment": function(){
            return cur+1;
        },
        "decrement": function(){
            return cur-1;
        },
        "reset": function(){
            cur =init;
            return cur;
        }}
        return counter;

Hi 🖐
 var createCounter = function(init) {
    let counter = init;
    return {
        increment: () => ++counter,
        decrement: () => --counter,
        reset: () => (counter = init),
    }
}

firstly, you don't want to use "", change it to just `increment: function`
secondly, you are returning cur+1. But you are not actually changing cur. So if you do a multiple operations of increment, the value will always be the original + 1.
What you want to do is to change the value of cur and return that, like:
```
increment: function(){
return cur = cur+1;
},
```
Even smoother would be to use pre/post-increment operator, this is functionally equivalent, it just looks nicer:
```
increment: function(){
return ++cur;
},
```
note that the ++ comes in front of the cur, because you want to first increment and then return the incremented value. 
Also if you don't use { } you don't need to add return and you can put it on one line if you make it an arrow function like this:
```
increment: () => ++cur,
```
ps: if you put three backticks (```) on a separate line above and below your code snippet, it gets formatted nicely like this.

