# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
What is needed to be doein the task in simple words?
* we have graph
* we need to find amount of the components (component is a set of nodes that are connected by edges)
* all of the nodes in such component also should be connected with the rest of it (like if we have graph `{0, 1, 2}` => there should be edges `{{0, 2}, {0, 3}, {1, 2}}`). This means that the number of edges of this node should be `component.size() - 1`.

You can use different approaches for it, but my fav is BFS .
*Yeah, maybe the best match here is DSU, but I don't like it XD*

Please, study BFS on your own, I don't want to take you time here to explain it.

But why BFS? What thoughts led me to this?
The answer is simple - in this problem (as I hope you can see) was asked to traverse the graph, so you have several options here and I like to do BFS. That's it =)

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We are going to make BFS for each node in `[0, ..., n - 1]`, mark what we have visit already, to note iterate one more time.

But to count the components that we are looking for we need to track which nodes are in this component. For this I gonna use `std::unordered_set` - it's simple to use use and fast enough.

So, how we will find the component:
1. Run BFS for some node.
2. Save nodes of this component to set.
3. Iterate over set and check if this node has `set.size() - 1` edges.

For more about algo, please see the code

> Please upvote if you like it!

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$ O(n^{(n + E)}) $$. This is because we have one main `for` ($$O(n)$$), than inside we have two additional loops:
    1. First for BFS with $$O(E)$$, where `E` is amount of edges in component.
    2. Second for iterating of the nodes in component with $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n + E)$$. This is because `graph` is the biggest memory structure.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int countCompleteComponents(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        // convert to something more usable
        std::vector<std::vector<int>> graph(n);
        for(const auto& edge: edges) {
            graph[edge[0]].push_back(edge[1]);
            graph[edge[1]].push_back(edge[0]);
        }

        // to mark each node that was visited
        std::vector<bool> visited(n);
        int result = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            // no need to iterate one more time
            if(visited[i]) {
                continue;
            }

            // to store one component
            std::unordered_set<int> localGraph;

            // BFS start
            std::queue<int> q;
            q.push(i);
            visited[i] = true;
            localGraph.insert(i);

            while(!q.empty()) {
                auto current = q.front();
                q.pop();

                for(auto next: graph[current]) {
                    if(!visited[next]) {
                        visited[next] = true;
                        localGraph.insert(next);
                        q.push(next);
                    }
                }
            }

            // to check if each node of component meets the requirements
            bool isComplete = true;
            for(const auto node: localGraph) {
                if(graph[node].size() != localGraph.size() - 1) {
                    isComplete = false;
                    break;
                }
            }

            // if yes, that is component we are looking for
            if(isComplete) {
                ++result;
            }
        }

        return result;
    }
};
```

