# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize the Graph: Create an adjacency list representation of the graph using a 2D vector graph, where graph[i] contains the neighbors of node i. This is done by iterating through the edges vector and adding each edge to the graph.

2. Initialize Variables: Initialize a variable res to keep track of the number of complete components. Also, create a boolean vector visited of size n to keep track of visited nodes.

3. Iterate Through Nodes: Iterate through all nodes in the graph from 0 to n-1.

4. DFS (Depth-First Search):

    - If the current node has not been visited (!visited[i]), initiate a DFS from this node.
    - In the DFS, the dfs function is called, which:
      Marks the current node as visited.
    - Increments the node count (number of nodes in the current component).
    - Increments the edge_c count by the number of neighbors (edges) of the current node.
    - Recursively explores unvisited neighbors.
    - Check for Complete Component:

5. After the DFS, check if the current component is complete. A component is considered complete if the number of nodes (node) multiplied by (node-1) equals the number of edges (edge_c). If this condition is met, increment the res count.
Return the Result:

6. After iterating through all nodes, the function returns the total count of complete components, which is stored in the res variable.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

