# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Though this might not be a best solution but I had this in my mind when I tried to solve this. There might other better approches, even I will try to look for it, but now lets check this.

So the idea here is if we check the numbers of nodes any vertex is connected to and also insert them in an set, and then check all those nodes if they connected to the same(hence same size also) vertexes or not.
After exploring one Node, we will traverse it and mark all the connected as visited true. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This is little complicated code to explain for me. 

**Step 1 :** create 2d vector for graph (here g);
**Step 2 :** build up an undirected graph
**Step 3 :** initialze count to 0, create set and visited vector to all false.
**Step 4 :** iterate through all the nodes if not visited.
**Step 5 :** insert it in set, then insert all the nodes connected with it in that set.
**Step 6 :** for temprary purpose intialize the flag with value true for every iteration of not visited nodes.
**Step 7 :** Now iterate through all the nodes and if the size of it is same as set(exclude the index i 'of iteration', hence s.size()-1) and also that size should match with size of the very first node connection (for index i).
**Step 8 :** if the all the elements are present in the set and also step 7 is correct then all good, else set flag false;
**Step 9 :** if flag is true increment count because this the complete component.
**Step 10 :** now considering the ith index as source, traverse the graph and mark all the visited nodes.
**Step 11 :** clear the set and go for the next iteration of the loop.
**Step 12 :** return count. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^2)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n^2)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

