# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

Use DFS and every time DFS restarts is a start of a new component 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

Takes $O(n + m)$ time using DFS; going through each component and check if the adjList == m - 1 takes $O(n)$ time because there are n total nodes that we go through and getting the length of a list takes $O(1)$ time

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

The space complexity is $O(n + m)$ to store the components, explored array, adjList. 

# Code
```
class Solution:
    def countCompleteComponents(self, n: int, edges: List[List[int]]) -> int:


        adjList = {}

        for i in range(n):
            adjList[i] = []

        for edge in edges:

            u = edge[0] 

            v = edge[1]

            adjList[u].append(v)

            adjList[v].append(u)

        explored = [False for i in range(n)]

        components = {}

        def search(v, component):

            explored[v] = True 

            components[component].append(v)

            for w in adjList[v]:
                if not explored[w]:
                    search(w, component)

        def dfs():
            component = 0 
            for i in range(n):
                if not explored[i]:
                    components[component] = []
                    search(i, component)
                    component += 1 

        dfs()

        completeCount = 0 


        for k in components:
            m = len(components[k])
            Complete = True
            for node in components[k]:
                if len(adjList[node]) != m - 1:
                    Complete = False 
                    break 
            if Complete == True:
                completeCount += 1

        return completeCount



```

