# Approach 1: do the work at compile time
The property of being _fascinating_ doesn't change, hence we can pre compute them at compile time. ```::isFascinating``` is inspired by [this post](https://leetcode.com/problems/check-if-the-number-is-fascinating/discuss/3622454/Bits-(O(1)-Space)).

```cpp
namespace {
constexpr bool isFascinating(int n) {
    int seen = 0;
    auto check = [&](int n) -> bool {
        while (n) {
            const int d =  n % 10;
            n /= 10;
            const int mask = 1 << d;
            if (d == 0 || seen & mask) return false;
            seen |= mask;
        }
        return true;
    };
    return check(n) && check(2 * n) && check(3 * n);
}

constexpr array<bool, 1000> gen_isF() {
    array<bool, 1000> ans = {};
    for (int i = 100; i < 1000; ++i) 
        ans[i] = isFascinating(i);
    return ans;
}

constexpr array<bool, 1000> isF = gen_isF();
}  // namespace

class Solution {
public:
    static bool isFascinating(int n) {
        return isF[n];
    }
};
```

**Complexity Analysis**
* Time complexity is $$O(1)$$ and

* Space comlexity is $$O(1)$$, even if we need to keep an array of 1000 booleans around.

# Approach 2: hard code it
It turns out there are only 4 _fascinating_ numbers: 192, 219, 273, and 327. We can just hard code that. Maybe that's consider cheating. :)

```cpp
    bool isFascinating(int n) {
        return n == 192 || n == 219 || n == 273 || n == 327;
    }
```

It's interesting how the compiler generates something that looks like binary search for this: https://godbolt.org/z/P9cr7fnE9

**Complexity Analysis**
* Time complexity is $$O(1)$$ and

* Space comlexity is $$O(1)$$.

