# Intuition
- If the main tank has less than 5 liters of fuel, the remaining fuel determines the maximum distance that can be traveled. Calculate the distance based on the remaining fuel and return it.
- Simulate the process of fuel consumption and transfer between the main tank and additional tank.
- In each iteration, if the main tank has at least 5 liters of fuel:
    - Add 50 to the distance traveled (10 km per liter for 5 liters).
    - Subtract 5 from the main tank fuel.
    - If there is fuel in the additional tank, transfer 1 liter to the main tank.
- When the main tank has less than 5 liters of fuel, calculate the distance based on the remaining fuel and add it to the total distance traveled.
- Return the total distance traveled.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
- If the main tank has less than 5 liters of fuel, calculate and return the distance that can be traveled with the remaining fuel.
- Simulate the process of fuel consumption and transfer between the main tank and additional tank.
- Add 50 to the distance traveled for every 5 liters of fuel in the main tank.
- If there is fuel in the additional tank, transfer 1 liter to the main tank for every 5 liters consumed.
- Calculate and add the distance that can be traveled with the remaining fuel in the main tank if it's less than 5 liters.
- Return the total distance traveled.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->


# Complexity
**- Time complexity:**
The time complexity of this code is O(max(mainTank, additionalTank)). In the worst case, both tanks need to be fully consumed before the loop breaks.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

**- Space complexity:**
The space complexity is O(1) as it uses only a constant amount of extra space for variables.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# C++
